e" data-parent=3D"#accordionDensityCalc">
      <div class=3D"card-body">
        <p><strong>EXAMPLE</strong>: If the length is 25 inches, the width =
is 24 inches and the height is 23 inches, multiply them as follows:</p>
        <ol>
        <li class=3D"number">25 X 24 X 23 =3D 13,800 cubic inches.</li>
        <li class=3D"number">Convert cubic inches to cubic feet by dividing=
 the cubic inch total by 1,728=E2=80=94the number of cubic inches in one cu=
bic foot. For example: 13,800 divided by 1,728 =3D 7.98 cubic feet.</li>
        <li class=3D"number">Dividing the weight of the shipment by the num=
ber of cubic feet will provide the density. For example: 90 pounds divided =
by 7.98 =3D 11.27 pounds per cubic foot.</li>
        </ol>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div><!-- /.card -->

  <div class=3D"card">
    <div class=3D"card-header" id=3D"headingTwo">
      <h2 class=3D"mb-0">
        <button class=3D"collapsed" type=3D"button" data-toggle=3D"collapse=
" data-target=3D"#collapseTwo" aria-expanded=3D"false" aria-controls=3D"col=
lapseTwo">
          How to Measure Palletized Freight
        </button>
      </h2>
    </div>
    <div id=3D"collapseTwo" class=3D"collapse" aria-labelledby=3D"headingTw=
o" data-parent=3D"#accordionDensityCalc">
      <div class=3D"card-body">
        <p><strong>EXAMPLE</strong>: If the pallet is 46 inches long, 42 in=
ches wide and 6 inches high, add the height of the pallet to the height of =
the shipment (23 inches) for a combined height of 29 inches.</p>
        <ol>
        <li class=3D"number">46 X 42 X 29 =3D 56,028 cubic inches.</li>
        <li class=3D"number">Next, convert the inches total to cubic feet b=
y dividing 56,028 by 1,728 =3D 32.42 cubic feet.</li>
        <li class=3D"number">The density then equals the weight 120 (90 pou=
nds for the shipment and approximately 30 pounds for the pallet) divided by=
 the cubic dimension: 120 divided by 32.42 =3D 3.70 pounds per cubic foot.<=
/li>
        </ol>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div><!-- /.card -->

  <div class=3D"card">
    <div class=3D"card-header" id=3D"headingThree">
      <h2 class=3D"mb-0">
        <button class=3D"collapsed" type=3D"button" data-toggle=3D"collapse=
" data-target=3D"#collapseThree" aria-expanded=3D"false" aria-controls=3D"c=
ollapseThree">
          How to Measure Cylindrical Freight
        </button>
      </h2>
    </div>
    <div id=3D"collapseThree" class=3D"collapse" aria-labelledby=3D"heading=
Three" data-parent=3D"#accordionDensityCalc">
      <div class=3D"card-body">
        <p>To determine the density of a cylindrical shaped object or any a=
rticle that's not square, rectangular or elliptical, multiply the greatest =
dimension on the cylindrical plane by itself, then multiply that result by =
the object's height or length. If the value is in cubic inches, divide the =
number by 1,728 cubic inches, then divide the weight by this number. The an=
swer will provide your density figure.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div><!-- /.card -->
</div><!-- /.accordion --></div><!-- /.widget-wrapper -->
